{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523526"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13904"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13904"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.04,0.09,0.05,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55867"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41413"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8850"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13030"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55867"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a rapidly growing, red, dome-shaped lesion on his left lower eyelid margin (Image). He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. There is no history of trauma or any other suspicious lesions. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lesion is 5 mm in diameter, shiny, and bleeds easily when touched though is not painful. There is no surrounding inflammation or ulceration.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Optical coherence tomography","Fine needle aspiration","Incisional biopsy","Mole mapping","Excisional biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a lesion characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Epyogenic granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as lobular capillary hemangioma. These are benign vascular lesions that can occur on the skin or mucous membranes, including the eyelid margin, secondary to minor trauma however there may be a lack of history such as in this case. The rapid growth, red appearance, and easy bleeding are typical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. It serves both diagnostic and therapeutic purposes. Complete excision allows for histopathological examination to confirm the diagnosis and rule out malignancy, while also removing the lesion entirely. This is particularly important for eyelid lesions due to their sensitive location and potential impact on vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is less appropriate in this case. While it can provide tissue for diagnosis, it doesn\u0027t completely remove the lesion and may lead to recurrence. For small, well-defined lesions like the one described, complete excision is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used for pyogenic granulomas. It is more commonly employed for cystic lesions or when trying to differentiate between inflammatory and neoplastic processes. For a solid, vascular lesion like a pyogenic granuloma, FNA would likely yield only blood and may not provide diagnostic information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMole mapping\u003C/strong\u003E is a technique used to monitor skin lesions, particularly moles, over time. It involves taking high-resolution photographs of the skin to track changes. While useful for monitoring chronic skin condition, monitoring suspicious lesions or assessing melanoma risk, it is not typically used for acute, rapidly growing lesions like pyogenic granulomas. In this case, immediate action (excisional biopsy) is more appropriate than long-term monitoring and conservative reviews.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptical coherence tomography\u003C/strong\u003E (OCT) is an imaging technique that can be useful in ophthalmology for evaluating retinal and corneal conditions. While it has some applications in assessing eyelid lesions, it\u0027s not typically the first-line investigation for suspected pyogenic granulomas. Excisional biopsy remains the gold standard for diagnosis and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing eyelid lesions, it is crucial to obtain a definitive diagnosis while also considering the cosmetic and functional aspects. Excisional biopsy achieves both these goals efficiently as well as lessens the chance of recurrence. Following excision, the specimen should be sent for histopathological examination to confirm the diagnosis of pyogenic granuloma and rule out any unexpected malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pyogenic granuloma is a benign vascular lesion that can occur on the eyelid margin.","Excisional biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosis and treatment of pyogenic granuloma."],"references":["Damen-van Beek Z, Opstelten W. A fast growing tumour. Australian Family Physician. 2015:44 (10). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/october/a-fast-growing-tumour","Yiasemides E. Pyogenic Granuloma.  The Australasian College of Dermatologists. 2019. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/pyogenic-granuloma/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13904"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20839"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20839"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/gGSDQZ0pNGAy0GpJcuQy7sk1SwiYD8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/gGSDQZ0pNGAy0GpJcuQy7sk1SwiYD8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41413"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T12:35:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T12:35:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55867"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt